Here's the recommended approach using a custom `Window` subclass with `Preferences` for fast state persistence:

**1. Create a ViewModel for your note page:**

```csharp
// ViewModels/NoteViewModel.cs
public class NoteViewModel : INotifyPropertyChanged
{
    private string _draftText = string.Empty;

    public string DraftText
    {
        get => _draftText;
        set { _draftText = value; PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, new(nameof(DraftText))); }
    }

    public event PropertyChangedEventHandler? PropertyChanged;
}
```

**2. Create a custom Window subclass that saves/restores state:**

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    private readonly NoteViewModel _noteVm;

    public AppWindow(Page page, NoteViewModel noteVm) : base(page)
    {
        _noteVm = noteVm;
    }

    protected override void OnCreated()
    {
        base.OnCreated();
        // Restore any draft from a previous session
        _noteVm.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        // App fully backgrounded — save the draft
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _noteVm.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        // Returning from background — restore in case OS discarded state
        _noteVm.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped, so save here too
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _noteVm.DraftText);
    }
}
```

**3. Wire it up in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    private readonly NoteViewModel _noteVm;

    public App(NoteViewModel noteVm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        _noteVm = noteVm;
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell(), _noteVm);
}
```

**4. Register in DI (`MauiProgram.cs`):**

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<NoteViewModel>();
builder.Services.AddSingleton<App>();
```

**5. Bind in your note page XAML:**

```xml
<Editor Text="{Binding DraftText}" Placeholder="Start typing..." />
```

### Key points

- **`OnStopped`** fires when the app is fully backgrounded — this is the right place to save.
- **`OnDestroying`** also saves because Android's back button can skip `Stopped` entirely.
- **`OnResumed`** restores state when returning from background.
- **`Preferences`** is used because it's fast and synchronous — lifecycle handlers must complete quickly (~1–2s) to avoid ANR on Android or watchdog kills on iOS.
- **`OnResumed` does NOT fire on first launch** — the initial sequence is `Created → Activated`, which is why we restore in `OnCreated` as well.
